3, the second ever international match.\n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[FA Cup]]'''\n** Winners (2): [[FA Cup Final 1879|1879]], [[FA Cup Final 1882|1882]]\n**''Runners-up (4)'': [[FA Cup Final 1875|1875]], [[FA Cup Final 1876|1876]], [[FA Cup Final 1881|1881]], [[FA Cup Final 1883|1883]]\n\n*'''[[Arthurian League]]'''\n** Premier Division Champions (2): 1992\u201393, 2004\u201305\n** Division One Champions (1): 1985\u201386\n** Division Two Champions (2nd XI) (4): 1992\u201393, 1997\u201398, 1999\u20132000, 2003\u201304\n** Division Three Champions (3rd XI) (2): 1995\u201396, 2004\u201305\n** Division Four Champions (4th XI) (2): 1989\u201390, 1993\u201394\n\n* '''[[Arthur Dunn Cup]]'''\n** Winners (2): 2004\u201305, 2009\u201310\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://twitter.com/oldetoniansafc Official Twitter]\n*{{fchd|name=Old Etonians|id=O-ETONIA}}\n{{Commons cat|Old Etonians F.C.}}\n\n{{coord|51|29|41.73|N|0|35|49.61|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1865]]\n[[Category:FA Cup winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Berkshire]]\n[[Category:1865 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Etonians_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Sidney R. Yates", "text_new": "{{Infobox Congressman\n| image name    = Sidney R. Yates.jpg\n|birth_name     = Sidney Richard Yates\n| birth_date    = August 27, 1909\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2000|10|5|1909|8|27}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| state         = [[Illinois]]\n| district      = [[Illinois's 9th congressional district|9th]]\n<!-- 2nd Tenure -->\n| term_start    = January 3, 1965\n| term_end      = January 3, 1999\n| predecessor   = [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward R. Finnegan]]\n| successor     = [[Jan Schakowsky]]\n<!-- 1st Tenure -->\n| term_start2   = January 3, 1949\n| term_end2     = January 3, 1963\n| predecessor2  = [[Robert Twyman]]\n| successor2    = [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward R. Finnegan]]\n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Chicago]] {{small|(B Ph, JD)}}\n| profession    = Attorney\n| spouse        = Adeline Holleb (1914\u20132002)\n| children      = Stephen R. Yates (1940\u20132000)\n| allegiance    = United States\n| branch        = [[United States Navy]]\n| serviceyears  = 1944\u20131946\n| unit          = [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, U.S. Navy|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]\n| rank          = [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]]\n| battles       = [[World War II]]\n}}\n'''Sidney Richard Yates''' (August 27, 1909&nbsp;\u2013 October 5, 2000) was a [[politician]] from the [[U.S. state|state]] of [[Illinois]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he is most notable for his long service as a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]].\n\nA native of [[Chicago]], Yates graduated from [[Lake View High School (Chicago)|Lake View High School]] in 1928.  He received bachelor's (1931) and law (1933) degrees from the [[University of Chicago]], was admitted to the bar, and practiced law in Chicago.  In addition to working as an attorney, in the 1930s Yates also played semiprofessional basketball.  He gained his initial experience in government as an attorney for the state bank receiver (1935-1937), and an assistant state attorney general specializing in [[Railway electric traction|traction railroads]] for the Illinois Commerce Commission (1937-1940).  During [[World War II]], Yates served in the [[United States Navy]] for two years (1944-1946) as an attorney based in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nIn 1948, Yates was elected to Congress, and he served from 1949 to 1963.  After an unsuccessful run against [[Everett Dirksen]] for the United States Senate in [[1962 United States Senate election in Illinois|1962]], in 1964 Yates was again elected to Congress.  he served from 1965 to 1999, and did not run for reelection in 1998.  He was a longtime member of the House [[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Appropriations Committee]], where he became known for staunch U.S. support of [[Israel]], and federal funding for parks, historical conservation, and the arts.  Yates was also an advocate for several liberal causes, including opposition to discrimination based on age.  At the time he concluded his service, he was the oldest person to ever serve in the House (age 89), and one of the longest-tenured members in the history of Congress (total House service of 48 years).\n\nYates died in Washington in 2000.  He was buried at Memorial Park Cemetery in [[Skokie, Illinois]].\n\n==Early life==\nYates was born in Chicago, Illinois, the youngest of six children of [[Lithuania]]n Jewish immigrants Louis and Ida Yates.<ref>\n{{citation |url= https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:XSPL-7D9 |title= United States Census, 1930 |website= [[FamilySearch]] |accessdate=March 24, 2018 }}</ref>  Yates grew up in Chicago and he graduated from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1931 with a [[Bachelor of Philosophy]] degree<ref>{{cite news |date=June 14, 1931 |title=Degrees Await 63 North Siders at U. of Chicago |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48792893/degrees-await/ |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, IL |page=Part 7, Page 3 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and received a [[Juris Doctor]] from the [[University of Chicago Law School]] in 1933.<ref>{{cite book |last=U.S. Congress |date=1959 |title=Official Congressional Directory |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j7pFAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA40 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=US Government Printing Office |page=40 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>  While in college, Yates joined the [[Pi Lambda Phi]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite book |date=1935 |title=The Frater of Pi Lambda Phi |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Frater_Pi_Lambda_Phi_Fraternity/3i3OAAAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=%22sidney%20yates%22 |location=Danbury, CT |publisher=Pi Lambda Phi Fraternity |page=26 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>  He also played basketball, and was selected for [[Big Ten Conference|All Big Ten]] honors.<ref>{{cite book |date=1948 |title=The International Teamster |volume=46 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_International_Teamster/WJVZAAAAYAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=%22big%20ten%20all-conference%22 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=International Brotherhood of Teamsters |page=97 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>  In the mid-1930s, he played semiprofessional basketball and practiced law.<ref name=\"Stout\">{{cite news |last=Stout |first=David |date=October 8, 2000 |title=Sidney R. Yates Dies at 91; Congressman Supported Arts |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/08/us/sidney-r-yates-dies-at-91-congressman-supported-arts.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York, NY}}</ref> Yates was an attorney for the Illinois state bank receiver from 1935 to 1937.<ref name=Pearson\">{{cite news |last=Pearson |first=Richard |date=October 7, 2000 |title=Longtime Congressman Sidney Yates Dies |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/2000/10/07/longtime-congressman-sidney-yates-dies/215e49a3-9177-482c-b9ff-ee032a656b40/ |work=[[Washington Post]] |location=Washington, DC}}</ref> From 1937 to 1940 he was an assistant state attorney general attached to the Illinois Commerce Commission as a traction attorney.<ref name=Pearson\"/>{{efn|\"Traction\" refers the Chicago public transit system, which included trains and trolleys powered by electric [[traction motor]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dorf |first1=Michael C. |last2=Van Dusen |first2=George |date=2019 |title=Clear it with Sid! |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Clear_It_with_Sid/JOuRDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22sidney+r.+yates%22+%22traction%22&pg=PT59 |location=Champaign, IL |publisher=University of Illinois Press |page=59 |isbn=978-0-2520-5128-9}}</ref>}} He served in the [[United States Navy]] during [[World War II]], assigned as an attorney for the Bureau of Ships in Washington, DC.<ref name=Pearson\"/> He is the longest-serving member ever of the United States House of Representatives from the state of [[Illinois]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Crass |first=Scott |date=2015 |title=Statesmen and Mischief Makers |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Statesmen_and_Mischief_Makers/fjemCgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22sidney+yates%22+longest+serving+congressman+from+illinois&pg=PT432 |location=Bloomington, IN |publisher=Xlibris |page=432 |isbn=978-1-5144-0384-6 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career in Congress==\nFrom 1949 to 1963 and 1965 to 1999, Yates served in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] as a [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democrat]]. Although the boundaries of his district changed over the years, it was always anchored in the Chicago lakefront. From the 1970s onward, Chicago's declining population resulted in the district spilling into the northern suburbs. By the time he retired, his district also included [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]], [[Des Plaines, Illinois|Des Plaines]], [[Glenview, Illinois|Glenview]], [[Rosemont, Illinois|Rosemont]] and [[Skokie, Illinois|Skokie]]. \n\nYates was one of the first congressmen to speak out against age discrimination, arguing in 1951 that mandatory retirement of workers was wrong and deprived older people of their ''right to lead a proud, productive and independent life.''\n\nDuring the late 1950s, after a series of lurid magazine articles and Hollywood films helped to sensationalize youth gangs and violence, Yates called for legislation to ban automatic-opening or [[switchblade]] knives, proclaiming that \"Vicious fantasies of omnipotence, idolatry...barbaric and sadistic atrocities, and monstrous violations of accepted values spring from the cult of the weapon, and the switchblade knife is included in this. Minus switchblade knives and the distorted feeling of power they beget\u2014power that is swaggering, reckless, and itching to express itself in violence\u2014our delinquent adolescents would be shorn of one of their most potent means of incitement to crime.\"<ref name=\"LEV\">Levine, Bernard R., ''[http://www.knife-expert.com/schr-pb.txt The Switchblade Menace]'', OKCA Newsletter (1993)</ref><ref>Knife World (August 1990)</ref><ref name=\"CON\">Switchblade Knives: Hearing, House Committee on Interstate and Foreign Commerce, Eighty-fifth Congress, Minutes of the Second Session, April 17, 1958</ref>  The ban on switchblade knives was eventually enacted into law as the Switchblade Knife Act of 1958.<ref name=\"CON\"/>  Rep. Yates and other congressmen supporting the Switchblade Knife Act believed that by stopping the importation and interstate sales of automatic knives (effectively halting sales of new switchblades), the law would reduce youth gang violence by blocking access to what had become a symbolic weapon.<ref name=\"LEV\"/><ref name=\"CON\"/><ref>Knife World Magazine (August 1990)</ref>  However, while switchblade imports, domestic production, and sales to lawful owners soon ended, later legislative research demonstrated that youth gang violence rates had in fact rapidly increased, as gang members began using firearms instead of knives.<ref>Clark, Charles S., ''Youth Gangs Worsening Violence Prompts Crackdowns and Community Mobilization'', Congressional Quarterly 1, 11 October 1991, pp. 753\u2013776</ref>\n\nYates was an unsuccessful candidate for the [[United States Senate]] in 1962 against Republican incumbent and [[Senate Minority Leader]] [[Everett Dirksen]]. He briefly served at the [[United Nations]] before returning to the House after the 1964 election. Fellow Democrat [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward Finnegan]] won Yates' old seat after his former district was merged with the 9th, but Chicago machine bosses persuaded him to accept a circuit judgeship in return for letting Yates take his old seat back. Yates served on the [[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Appropriations Committee]] throughout his career and chaired the Interior Subcommittee from 1975 to 1995. On this committee he supported environmental programs and the [[National Endowment for the Arts]].\n\nYates remained on good terms with both liberal reformers and machine politicians in Chicago throughout his career. He also served on the Foreign Operations subcommittee and was a strong advocate of American support for [[Israel]]. He worked hand-in-hand with his chief of staff, [[Mary Anderson Bain|Mary Bain]], to preserve federal funding for the arts and for Natural Heritage Preservation programs, and to establish the [[U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum]].\n\nIn 1993, he was presented with the [[Presidential Citizens Medal]] by President [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] and in 1997 he received the [[Four Freedoms Award]] for Freedom of Speech<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rooseveltinstitute.org/four-freedoms-awards |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325223647/http://www.rooseveltinstitute.org/four-freedoms-awards |archivedate=2015-03-25 }}</ref> In 1999, the Auditors Building in [[Washington, DC]], was renamed the [[Sidney Yates Building]] in his honor.<ref name=DMUSDA>[http://www.dm.usda.gov/buildings.htm#Yates%20Building Histories of the USDA Headquarters Complex Buildings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721071326/http://www.dm.usda.gov/buildings.htm |date=2011-07-21 }}, U.S. Department of Agriculture Departmental Management website, accessed July 28, 2011</ref>\n\nIn his closing months of service, he surpassed [[Robert L. Doughton]] as the oldest person ever to serve in the House (Yates was surpassed in this record by [[Ralph Hall]] (R-Texas) in 2012). He holds the record as the [[List of members of the United States Congress by longevity of service|10th longest-serving member]] in the history of the US Congress, and also has the longest tenure of all members whose time in Congress included a break in service.\n\n==Family==\nYates was married to Adeline Holleb (1914\u20132002) for 65 years.  They were the parents of Stephen R. Yates (1940-2000), who served as an Illinois circuit court.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Jewish members of the United States Congress]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|Y000013}}\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511015407/http://bulk.resource.org/gpo.gov/papers/2000/2000_vol2_2063.pdf |date=May 11, 2010 |title=''Statement on the Death of Representative Sidney R. Yates'' }}\n* {{C-SPAN|sidneyyates}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state= Illinois\n|district= 9\n|before = [[Robert J. Twyman]]\n|years = January 3, 1949&nbsp;\u2013 January 3, 1963\n|after = [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward R. Finnegan]]}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state= Illinois\n|district= 9\n|before = [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward R. Finnegan]]\n|years = January 3, 1965&nbsp;\u2013 January 3, 1999\n|after = [[Jan Schakowsky]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, Sidney R.}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Jewish members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Illinois lawyers]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Presidential Citizens Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Congressman\n| image name    = Sidney R. Yates.jpg\n|birth_name     = Sidney Richard Yates\n| birth_date    = August 27, 1909\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2000|10|5|1909|8|27}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| state         = [[Illinois]]\n| district      = [[Illinois's 9th congressional district|9th]]\n<!-- 2nd Tenure -->\n| term_start    = January 3, 1965\n| term_end      = January 3, 1999\n| predecessor   = [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward R. Finnegan]]\n| successor     = [[Jan Schakowsky]]\n<!-- 1st Tenure -->\n| term_start2   = January 3, 1949\n| term_end2     = January 3, 1963\n| predecessor2  = [[Robert Twyman]]\n| successor2    = [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward R. Finnegan]]\n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Chicago]] {{small|(B Ph, JD)}}\n| profession    = Attorney\n| spouse        = Adeline Holleb (1914\u20132002)\n| children      = Stephen R. Yates (1940\u20132000)\n| allegiance    = United States\n| branch        = [[United States Navy]]\n| serviceyears  = 1944\u20131946\n| unit          = [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, U.S. Navy|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]\n| rank          = [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]]\n| battles       = [[World War II]]\n}}\n'''Sidney Richard Yates''' (August 27, 1909&nbsp;\u2013 October 5, 2000) was a [[politician]] from the [[U.S. state|state]] of [[Illinois]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he is most notable for his long service as a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]].\n\nA native of [[Chicago]], Yates graduated from [[Lake View High School (Chicago)|Lake View High School]] in 1928.  He received bachelor's (1931) and law (1933) degrees from the [[University of Chicago]], was admitted to the bar, and practiced law in Chicago.  In addition to working as an attorney, in the 1930s Yates also played semiprofessional basketball.  He gained his initial experience in government as an attorney for the state bank receiver (1935-1937), and an assistant state attorney general specializing in [[Railway electric traction|traction railroads]] for the Illinois Commerce Commission (1937-1940).  During [[World War II]], Yates served in the [[United States Navy]] for two years (1944-1946) as an attorney based in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nIn 1948, Yates was elected to Congress, and he served from 1949 to 1963.  After an unsuccessful run against [[Everett Dirksen]] for the United States Senate in [[1962 United States Senate election in Illinois|1962]], in 1964 Yates was again elected to Congress.  he served from 1965 to 1999, and did not run for reelection in 1998.  He was a longtime member of the House [[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Appropriations Committee]], where he became known for staunch U.S. support of [[Israel]], and federal funding for parks, historical conservation, and the arts.  Yates was also an advocate for several liberal causes, including opposition to discrimination based on age.  At the time he concluded his service, he was the oldest person to ever serve in the House (age 89), and one of the longest-tenured members in the history of Congress (total House service of 48 years).\n\nYates died in Washington in 2000.  He was buried at Memorial Park Cemetery in [[Skokie, Illinois]].\n\n==Early life==\nYates was born in Chicago, Illinois, the youngest of six children of [[Lithuania]]n Jewish immigrants Louis and Ida Yates.<ref>\n{{citation |url= https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:XSPL-7D9 |title= United States Census, 1930 |website= [[FamilySearch]] |accessdate=March 24, 2018 }}</ref>  Yates grew up in Chicago and he graduated from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1931 with a [[Bachelor of Philosophy]]<ref>{{cite news |date=June 14, 1931 |title=Degrees Await 63 North Siders at U. of Chicago |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48792893/degrees-await/ |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, IL |page=Part 7, Page 3 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and received a [[Juris Doctor]] from the [[University of Chicago Law School]] in 1933.<ref>{{cite book |last=U.S. Congress |date=1959 |title=Official Congressional Directory |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j7pFAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA40 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=US Government Printing Office |page=40 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>  While in college, Yates joined the [[Pi Lambda Phi]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite book |date=1935 |title=The Frater of Pi Lambda Phi |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Frater_Pi_Lambda_Phi_Fraternity/3i3OAAAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=%22sidney%20yates%22 |location=Danbury, CT |publisher=Pi Lambda Phi Fraternity |page=26 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>  He also played basketball, and was selected for [[Big Ten Conference|All Big Ten]] honors.<ref>{{cite book |date=1948 |title=The International Teamster |volume=46 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_International_Teamster/WJVZAAAAYAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=%22big%20ten%20all-conference%22 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=International Brotherhood of Teamsters |page=97 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>  In the mid-1930s, he played semiprofessional basketball and practiced law.<ref name=\"Stout\">{{cite news |last=Stout |first=David |date=October 8, 2000 |title=Sidney R. Yates Dies at 91; Congressman Supported Arts |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/08/us/sidney-r-yates-dies-at-91-congressman-supported-arts.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York, NY}}</ref> Yates was an attorney for the Illinois state bank receiver from 1935 to 1937.<ref name=Pearson\">{{cite news |last=Pearson |first=Richard |date=October 7, 2000 |title=Longtime Congressman Sidney Yates Dies |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/2000/10/07/longtime-congressman-sidney-yates-dies/215e49a3-9177-482c-b9ff-ee032a656b40/ |work=[[Washington Post]] |location=Washington, DC}}</ref> From 1937 to 1940 he was an assistant state attorney general attached to the Illinois Commerce Commission as a traction attorney.<ref name=Pearson\"/>{{efn|\"Traction\" refers the Chicago public transit system, which included trains and trolleys powered by electric [[traction motor]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dorf |first1=Michael C. |last2=Van Dusen |first2=George |date=2019 |title=Clear it with Sid! |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Clear_It_with_Sid/JOuRDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22sidney+r.+yates%22+%22traction%22&pg=PT59 |location=Champaign, IL |publisher=University of Illinois Press |page=59 |isbn=978-0-2520-5128-9}}</ref>}} He served in the [[United States Navy]] during [[World War II]], assigned as an attorney for the Bureau of Ships in Washington, DC.<ref name=Pearson\"/> He is the longest-serving member ever of the United States House of Representatives from the state of [[Illinois]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Crass |first=Scott |date=2015 |title=Statesmen and Mischief Makers |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Statesmen_and_Mischief_Makers/fjemCgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22sidney+yates%22+longest+serving+congressman+from+illinois&pg=PT432 |location=Bloomington, IN |publisher=Xlibris |page=432 |isbn=978-1-5144-0384-6 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career in Congress==\nFrom 1949 to 1963 and 1965 to 1999, Yates served in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] as a [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democrat]]. Although the boundaries of his district changed over the years, it was always anchored in the Chicago lakefront. From the 1970s onward, Chicago's declining population resulted in the district spilling into the northern suburbs. By the time he retired, his district also included [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]], [[Des Plaines, Illinois|Des Plaines]], [[Glenview, Illinois|Glenview]], [[Rosemont, Illinois|Rosemont]] and [[Skokie, Illinois|Skokie]]. \n\nYates was one of the first congressmen to speak out against age discrimination, arguing in 1951 that mandatory retirement of workers was wrong and deprived older people of their ''right to lead a proud, productive and independent life.''\n\nDuring the late 1950s, after a series of lurid magazine articles and Hollywood films helped to sensationalize youth gangs and violence, Yates called for legislation to ban automatic-opening or [[switchblade]] knives, proclaiming that \"Vicious fantasies of omnipotence, idolatry...barbaric and sadistic atrocities, and monstrous violations of accepted values spring from the cult of the weapon, and the switchblade knife is included in this. Minus switchblade knives and the distorted feeling of power they beget\u2014power that is swaggering, reckless, and itching to express itself in violence\u2014our delinquent adolescents would be shorn of one of their most potent means of incitement to crime.\"<ref name=\"LEV\">Levine, Bernard R., ''[http://www.knife-expert.com/schr-pb.txt The Switchblade Menace]'', OKCA Newsletter (1993)</ref><ref>Knife World (August 1990)</ref><ref name=\"CON\">Switchblade Knives: Hearing, House Committee on Interstate and Foreign Commerce, Eighty-fifth Congress, Minutes of the Second Session, April 17, 1958</ref>  The ban on switchblade knives was eventually enacted into law as the Switchblade Knife Act of 1958.<ref name=\"CON\"/>  Rep. Yates and other congressmen supporting the Switchblade Knife Act believed that by stopping the importation and interstate sales of automatic knives (effectively halting sales of new switchblades), the law would reduce youth gang violence by blocking access to what had become a symbolic weapon.<ref name=\"LEV\"/><ref name=\"CON\"/><ref>Knife World Magazine (August 1990)</ref>  However, while switchblade imports, domestic production, and sales to lawful owners soon ended, later legislative research demonstrated that youth gang violence rates had in fact rapidly increased, as gang members began using firearms instead of knives.<ref>Clark, Charles S., ''Youth Gangs Worsening Violence Prompts Crackdowns and Community Mobilization'', Congressional Quarterly 1, 11 October 1991, pp. 753\u2013776</ref>\n\nYates was an unsuccessful candidate for the [[United States Senate]] in 1962 against Republican incumbent and [[Senate Minority Leader]] [[Everett Dirksen]]. He briefly served at the [[United Nations]] before returning to the House after the 1964 election. Fellow Democrat [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward Finnegan]] won Yates' old seat after his former district was merged with the 9th, but Chicago machine bosses persuaded him to accept a circuit judgeship in return for letting Yates take his old seat back. Yates served on the [[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Appropriations Committee]] throughout his career and chaired the Interior Subcommittee from 1975 to 1995. On this committee he supported environmental programs and the [[National Endowment for the Arts]].\n\nYates remained on good terms with both liberal reformers and machine politicians in Chicago throughout his career. He also served on the Foreign Operations subcommittee and was a strong advocate of American support for [[Israel]]. He worked hand-in-hand with his chief of staff, [[Mary Anderson Bain|Mary Bain]], to preserve federal funding for the arts and for Natural Heritage Preservation programs, and to establish the [[U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum]].\n\nIn 1993, he was presented with the [[Presidential Citizens Medal]] by President [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] and in 1997 he received the [[Four Freedoms Award]] for Freedom of Speech<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rooseveltinstitute.org/four-freedoms-awards |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325223647/http://www.rooseveltinstitute.org/four-freedoms-awards |archivedate=2015-03-25 }}</ref> In 1999, the Auditors Building in [[Washington, DC]], was renamed the [[Sidney Yates Building]] in his honor.<ref name=DMUSDA>[http://www.dm.usda.gov/buildings.htm#Yates%20Building Histories of the USDA Headquarters Complex Buildings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721071326/http://www.dm.usda.gov/buildings.htm |date=2011-07-21 }}, U.S. Department of Agriculture Departmental Management website, accessed July 28, 2011</ref>\n\nIn his closing months of service, he surpassed [[Robert L. Doughton]] as the oldest person ever to serve in the House (Yates was surpassed in this record by [[Ralph Hall]] (R-Texas) in 2012). He holds the record as the [[List of members of the United States Congress by longevity of service|10th longest-serving member]] in the history of the US Congress, and also has the longest tenure of all members whose time in Congress included a break in service.\n\n==Family==\nYates was married to Adeline Holleb (1914\u20132002) for 65 years.  They were the parents of Stephen R. Yates (1940-2000), who served as an Illinois circuit court.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Jewish members of the United States Congress]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|Y000013}}\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511015407/http://bulk.resource.org/gpo.gov/papers/2000/2000_vol2_2063.pdf |date=May 11, 2010 |title=''Statement on the Death of Representative Sidney R. Yates'' }}\n* {{C-SPAN|sidneyyates}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state= Illinois\n|district= 9\n|before = [[Robert J. Twyman]]\n|years = January 3, 1949&nbsp;\u2013 January 3, 1963\n|after = [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward R. Finnegan]]}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state= Illinois\n|district= 9\n|before = [[Edward Rowan Finnegan|Edward R. Finnegan]]\n|years = January 3, 1965&nbsp;\u2013 January 3, 1999\n|after = [[Jan Schakowsky]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, Sidney R.}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Jewish members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Illinois lawyers]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Presidential Citizens Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidney_R._Yates"}
